  <static seed="284" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicMath/FractionApplication/FractionDivisionWordProblems30.pg">
    <statement><p>A food bank just received <m>21</m> kilograms of emergency food. Each family in need is to receive <m>{{\frac{3}{8}}}</m> kilograms of food. How many families can be served with the <m>21</m> kilograms of food?</p>
<p><fillin characters="10" name="AnSwEr0001"/> families can be served with the <m>21</m> kilograms of food.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>56</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>We can address this problem as repeatedly taking away <m>{{\frac{3}{8}}}</m> kilograms from <m>21</m> kilograms, which implies a division problem:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 
\begin{aligned}[t]
   21 \div {{\frac{3}{8}}} 
      \amp = \frac{21}{1} \cdot \frac{8}{3}  \\
      \amp = \frac{7}{1} \cdot \frac{8}{1}  \\
      \amp = \frac{7\cdot8}{1 \cdot 1} \\
      \amp = {56}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p><m>{56}</m> families can be served with the <m>21</m> kilograms of food.</p>
</solution>
